explanation:
For each symbol: brief reason why it is required to determine whether any use of <string.h> routines (or code paths leading to them) could produce out-of-bounds accesses when analyzing OS_ObjectIdGetById

OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit — direct callee; its implementation may call functions that use string routines or manipulate buffers while initializing the token/transaction.
OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex — direct callee; converts an ID to an array index and is passed &token->obj_idx — must inspect for any string handling or buffer writes.
OS_ObjectIdConvertToken — direct callee; performs token conversion and may call routines that use string functions or otherwise access token fields.
OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel — direct callee on error path; may perform cleanup that involves string ops or buffer access (and unlocks global state).
OS_GetMaxForObjectType — called by transaction/init/to-array-index; needed to understand bounds/limits used in index calculations that might interact with string/buffer ops.
OS_Lock_Global — called by transaction init; included because locking/unlocking pairs (with OS_Unlock_Global) define critical sections for routines that might manipulate shared buffers.
OS_Unlock_Global — called by convert/cancel; needed to follow control flow and ensure cleanup paths that might call string functions are analyzed.
OS_ObjectIdToSerialNumber_Impl — callee of ToArrayIndex; may perform conversions that use memory/string ops — include to inspect any string.h usage.
OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl — callee of ToArrayIndex and other callers; may access type/name buffers or call string functions.
OS_printf — appears as a callee in ToArrayIndex and other related functions; its implementation (or uses of formatted output) can involve string handling that must be checked for buffer overflows.
UT_ExecuteBasicHandler — test-harness stub callable from ToArrayIndex; include because unit-test stubs may simulate behavior that calls string routines.
UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr — test-harness stub; include for the same reason as other UT stubs.
OS_ObjectIdGlobalFromToken — callee of ConvertToken; may access global object tables or names with string ops.
OS_ObjectIdFromToken — callee of ConvertToken; resolves token to object info — may index into arrays or copy strings.
OS_ObjectIdIsValid — callee of ConvertToken; used to validate tokens/IDs — may compare strings or bounds.
OS_ObjectIdEqual — callee of ConvertToken; equality checks may involve string comparisons.
OS_WaitForStateChange — callee of ConvertToken; may perform operations while waiting that touch buffers.
OS_object_token_t — type of token pointer; needed to know the layout, sizes and pointer fields (obj_idx, obj_id, and any internal buffers) to determine whether any string functions could access out-of-bounds memory.
OS_SUCCESS — return-code constant used for control-flow decisions; required to determine which code paths (and thus which callees) are executed.
OS_lock_mode_t — parameter type; included for completeness if lock mode affects code paths taken in transaction/init routines.
osal_objtype_t — parameter type; affects behavior of ToArrayIndex/ConvertToken and thus what buffers/limits are used.
osal_id_t — parameter type for id; size/representation matters if passed to conversion routines that may do string/array operations.
int32 — return type definition (sanity) — included for completeness to interpret return values and control flow.

In short: include all direct callees and the downstream functions that manipulate tokens, object tables, indices or perform printing/stubbed behavior, plus the token/type definitions and control constants. These are the symbols required to trace whether any string.h functions are invoked on pointers or buffers derived from the token/ID/indices in a way that could access beyond object bounds.
